node.text:
Kenya is home to many vulnerable and endangered species including lions, giraffes and the world's only two surviving northern white rhino species.

It is also a transit route for migratory whales, dolphins and endangered turtles.

The country is counting all of its animals - but how and why? Click the link in our bio to find out more.

#Kenya #Africa #BBCNews

node.title: Kenya holds biggest ever animal census

#Afghanistan #BBCNews

node.text:
The 12 queens of RuPaul's Drag Race UK season three have been revealed, including the show's first female queen - Victoria Scone.

The 27-year-old from Cardiff is known as an 'AFAB' (assigned female at birth) queen, and says she's constantly faced criticism for not being a "proper drag queen".

Also taking part is Choriza May, a drag queen from Spain who's now living in Newcastle and Veronica Green, 35, who's back for a second chance after a positive Covid-19 test forced her to leave season two.

The new series starts next month on @bbcthree.

#DragRaceUK #DragQueen #BBCNews

node.title: Meet the new Drag Race UK queens 👑

Small numbers of Afghans have marked the country's Independence Day by taking to the streets waving their black, red and green national flag, in protest against the Taliban's takeover of the country.

The militants have been replacing the national flag with their own white one.

You shall go the ball! 

Sir Andrew Lloyd Webber's Cinderella is finally opening in the West End.

The show had been scheduled to open last year but was delayed by the Covid pandemic meant  Andrew Lloyd Webber’s Cinderella is only now ready to go to the ball.

The tale has been made more relevant for today’s audiences by Killing Eve and Promising Young Woman writer Emerald Fennell.

The BBC spoke to both Fennell and Lloyd Webber and also to star Carrie Hope Fletcher just ahead of the show’s press night.The show's star, Carrie Hope Fletcher, who plays Cinderella in the production says the cast "cannot wait to get in front of that full capacity audience."

node.title: Cinderella finally opens in London's West End

“British soldiers were my brothers.”

An Afghan interpreter who worked alongside the British army has pleaded with the UK Prime Minister to evacuate him and his family from Afghanistan.

Ahmed (not his real name) had received permission to travel to the UK last week, but a day later the Taliban seized control of the capital, Kabul.

He now fears for his safety and has requested a "pathway to safety" from the UK government and says "everyone who worked with coalition forces need to be relocated as soon as possible."

Tap the link in our bio to read more about his plight in the wake of the Taliban’s takeover of Afghanistan.

Wildfires have spread across Europe as many countries experience extreme heatwaves.

While these fires have a natural role to play in the ecological cycle, climate change means they may be more likely and severe.

The fires are not just being seen in Europe - countries like the US, Israel and Algeria have also battled with out-of-control blazes.

node.text:
The heavy rainfall that led to deadly floods in Germany and Belgium in July was influenced by human-induced warming, scientists said.

The floods, which had shocked weather forecasters and local authorities, killed at least 220 people as towns and villages were swamped.

Researchers said global heating made rainfall events like this up to nine times more likely in Western Europe. Meanwhile, human-driven climate change also made downpours in the region more intense by 3% to 19%.
 
With continued greenhouse gas emissions and rising temperatures, the heavy rainfall that brought misery to parts of Europe will become more common, experts warned.

"We must reduce greenhouse gas emissions as quickly as possible, as well as improving emergency warning and management systems and making our infrastructure 'climate resilient',” said Professor Hayley Fowler from Newcastle University.

Tap the link in our bio for more on this story.

(📸: Getty Images)

#ClimateChange #Europe #BBCNews

The record-breaking flooding began on Saturday, submerging entire roads and taking out telephone and power lines.

Kenya is home to many vulnerable and endangered species including lions, giraffes and the world's only two surviving northern white rhino species.

It is also a transit route for migratory whales, dolphins and endangered turtles.

The country is counting all of its animals - but how and why? Click the link in our bio to find out more.

node.text:
For the first time in 17 months, the Changing of the Guard ceremony at Buckingham Palace has taken place. 🇬🇧

Members of the public gathered to watch the event, which has been happening in London since 1656, but was paused due to the Covid pandemic.

The traditional ceremony usually last around 45 minutes and signifies a new battalion taking post to protect the Queen.

Tap the link in our bio to read more about the history of the popular London spectacle.

(📷 PA)

node.text:
"We're not going to accept any sort of aggression."

An anti-Taliban resistance group in Afghanistan says it has thousands of people ready to fight.

The Panjshir region - in particular the Panjshir Valley - is famous for having successfully fought off invasions, including from Soviet forces during the Soviet-Afghan war from 1979 to 1989, and the Taliban in the 1990s.

Now, the region is still under the control of National Resistance Front of Afghanistan (NRF), which was founded by Ahmad Massoud - the son of Afghan resistance hero Ahmad Shah Massoud.

Tap the link in our bio for more on what Ali Nazary, head of foreign relations for the NRF, told the BBC about the groups demands for peace.

#Afghanistan #BBCNews

The BBC's Lyse Doucet reports from Kabul airport as evacuations continue with Afghan's heading to unknown futures.

She says there are children and families "not knowing what kind of life they're heading to".
 
Tap the link in our bio for more on the situation in the country and the people fleeing for their lives.
 
#Afghanistan #BBCNews

node.text:
This is the plane making headlines for carrying Afghans to safety from the Taliban, the Boeing C-17 Globemaster III.

The four-engined transport plane that has been at the centre of the airlift from Hamid Karzai International Airport – hitting headlines after the US managed to evacuate 823 Afghans on board a single C-17 flight on 15 August. 

One Afghan woman even gave birth to a baby girl on a C-17 on Sunday. She went into labour as the flight was en route to Ramstein Air Base in Germany, and medical personnel helped deliver the child in the plane's cargo hold once it had landed.

Developed in the 1980s and first flown in the 1990s, it is now used by countries around the world to shuttle troops, cargo and sometimes people in danger.

Tap the link in our bio for more on the plane and how it has been used around the world.

(📷 Getty Images, US Air Mobility Command)

It’s a girl!
A woman evacuated from Afghanistan as the chaos in the country continues has given birth on an evacuation flight.
 
US Air Mobility Command posted on Twitter about the woman, who went into labour en route to Ramstein Air Base in Germany.
 
Medical personnel boarded the plane after it landed and delivered the baby girl in the aircraft's cargo hold.
 
Both baby and mother are said to be in good condition.
 
Click the link in our bio to read how the pilots decision to descend in altitude helped the mother.

(📸:US Air Mobility Command)
 
#Afghanistan #US #BBCNews

After 10 months at sea and a 3,000 miles journey, a message in a bottle has made its way from Canada to south Wales.

Amanda Tidmarsh, 52, from Brynna, Wales, was walking her two rescue dogs along the beach when she noticed the bottle mixed up with seaweed.

She said she was "so excited" to find it, having previously joked with her family that she was "always on the hunt for treasure".

The note appears to be from a snow crab fisherman named John Graham, who left his email for the finder to contact him.

Click the link in our bio to read if Amanda contacted John.

(📸:Amanda Tidmarsh)

node.text:
Antibody tests are to be widely offered to the UK public to find out more about how much natural protection people have after getting coronavirus.
 
Anyone over 18 will be able to opt in when having a PCR test - of those who test positive, up to 8,000 will be sent two home antibody tests.
 
The first of the finger-prick tests would have to be done as soon as possible after the positive result, so the body would not have time to generate a detectable antibody response to the infection.
 
Click the link in our bio to read more about Antibody testing. 

(📸: Getty)
